Um, today I flew this plane.
First complaint: we need cute flight logbooks. Black is too boring, and pink is actually more like salmon red.
I've wanted to fly since I was a kid.
Today my dream came true... I flew a plane today. I'm still not fully believing it.
flightaware data.
I plan to try again this Saturday. The weather doesn't look too good now, but today is just Monday.
It seems that the challenges in this area are beginning to show. Due to the FAA's stance on certain medications, I may have difficulty obtaining a medical certificate.
This is not impossible, but it will take a lot of time and involve a lot of extra work.
Although this is a bit discouraging, it's just another problem that needs to be solved, and it seems "definitely" solvable at the moment. It just requires a lot of time and money.
If you want to know what challenges I will face next:
FAA doesn't like ADHD. If you are taking medication for ADHD, you definitely won't be able to get a medical certificate.
https://youtu.be/W5JSfq6LLAU?si=xIxPaY8ayqqNSj4c
If I ever have the opportunity to customize my plane's tail number, it must be a variant of N1337_, where _ represents any available letter character.
Of course, the sun will definitely rise as usual while I'm not around, haha. That's really boring.
I have to fly again. But this terrible weather is really not cooperating.
Welcome to the world of general aviation! 😜
Based on the ads YouTube thinks I should see, the videos it recommends to me, and the comments, I feel that airlines tend to be conservative in their tracking.
If the weather allows, I will fly again on Saturday.
Also, I found a pink flight logbook.
Good morning Saturday. I did this today ^_^
#TeaganAir
The flight logbook has officially been put into use. I have 2.3 hours of flight time recorded ^_^
#TeaganAir
If you let me describe what it feels like to fly a small plane, I would say it's like driving a combination of a motorcycle/ATV and a boat at 4000 feet in the air.
On the ground, the situation changes rapidly. There is a certain degree of instability on the ground, so you need a motorcycle/ATV.
Also, you might not know that when driving an airplane on the ground, you use your feet to control the direction, not the control yoke. It uses the rudder pedals and brakes. It's definitely not a car.
When flying in the air, you will feel turbulence and shaking, similar to riding a boat on water. Although you can control the airplane, sometimes the airflow can make you a bit disoriented, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just like sailors adapt to sailing.
Regarding this, there's also a random little trivia:
Flying is very physically demanding. My back and legs are really sore today, feeling like I've been to the gym.
This is definitely not as simple as going for a drive on Sunday. In my novice opinion, it's more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, happy Saturday. Welcome to 4000 feet up high.
Tomorrow I will fly again, and we will practice stalls and slow flight.
Today's weather was a bit unstable, but super fun. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed once dropped to 16 miles per hour, while the airspeed was still at 65 miles per hour.
Today was sunny, and although the high altitude was a bit foggy, the view was still great.
